==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wrack
<hw>Wrack</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A thin, flying cloud; a
rack.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wrack</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wrack
<hw>Wrack</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To rack; to torment.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wrack</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wrack
<hw>Wrack</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>wrak</ets> wreck. See
<er>Wreck</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Wreck; ruin; destruction.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<au>Chaucer.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧A world devote to universal
<xex>wrack</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- used now mainly in the phrase <xex>wrack and ruin</xex> -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any marine vegetation cast up on the shore,
especially plants of the genera <gen>Fucus</gen>, <gen>Laminaria</gen>,
and <gen>Zostera</gen>, which are most abundant on northern
shores.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Coarse seaweed of any
kind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Wrack grass</b></col>, or <col><b>Grass
wrack</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>eelgrass.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wrack</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Wrack
<hw>Wrack</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To wreck.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wrackful</ent>⟦br⟧
